# crates/ctx-verify/src/checks.rs

Defines the fixed catalog of agent-checkpoint checks (`fmt`, `clippy`,
`doc`, `test`, `rationale`, `workspace_lints`, `no_allow`, `machete`,
`contracts`, `architecture`, `retired_terms`) and orchestrates running a
selected subset through a [`Runner`], parsing each tool's output into
[`Diagnostic`]s and assembling one [`Report`].

`fmt` is listed first and is the only check that *mutates* — it runs
`cargo fmt --all` and applies formatting rather than reporting on it
(`noop_parser` always returns empty; failure is caught only via nonzero
exit). Every other check is read-only/report-only. The `SPECS` order
matters only for `fmt`'s position; `run_selected` stores results in a
`BTreeMap` so output order is alphabetical by name, not spec order.

Each `Spec` pairs a tool invocation with a `Parser` function: `compiler_parser`
expects clippy/rustdoc `--message-format=json` output, `script_parser` scans
combined stdout+stderr for `FAIL:` lines (shared contract with the
`scripts/*.sh`/`.py` checks — changing their output format breaks parsing
here), and `test_parser` greps for `FAILED`/`error[`/`error:` substrings in
`cargo test` output (fragile pattern match, not a real test-harness parser).

`effective_args` injects `-p <package>` right after the subcommand for
`cargo`-tool specs when `package` is `Some`; non-cargo script checks silently
ignore package scoping. `run_spec` distinguishes three outcomes: `ToolMissing`
becomes `CheckReport::skipped()`, other spawn errors become `errored()`
(carrying the message, kept distinct from a real failing check), and a
completed-but-failed run with zero parsed diagnostics gets a synthesized
`failure_hint` (last non-empty line of stderr/stdout) so failures are never
silently empty.

`run_selected(runner, max, only, package) -> Report` is the sole public
entry point; `only: None` runs the full default set (used for the agent
checkpoint), `Some(names)` restricts to a name-matching subset (tight-loop
`--checks`/single-check use). `max` caps diagnostics per check via
`CheckReport::build`.